        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-06-18T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-06-18T12:00:00-05:00" n="978" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d978">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.932/6–1345: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hurley</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-06-18T13:00:00-04:00">June 18, 1945—1 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>928. Department has received a letter from Soong dated June 13<note n="69" xml:id="d978fn69">Not printed; it was addressed to the Assistant Secretary
                        of State (Clayton).</note> stating that he has appointed Dr. Kan Lee,
                    Commercial Counselor of Embassy, to begin preliminary discussions with us
                    regarding proposed treaty of friendship, commerce and navigation. Soong states
                    Kan Lee will return to Chungking after conversations to discuss relevant points
                    with various departments of Chinese Government concerned with treaty. This does
                    not change the plan to conduct the negotiations in Chungking.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
